Differential gene expression with DESeq2

Barbara Vreede
10 September 2018

Studying gene expression

  • Genes are the bits of DNA that encode proteins (building blocks)
  • DNA -> RNA -> Protein
  • Which genes are active?
  • How much?
  • Is there a difference in expression levels between contexts?

RNAseq technology and output

  • Next Generation Sequencing: rapid and affordable
  • RNASeq: sequences RNA in a quantified manner
  • Results are bits of sequences (~75bp) that need to be mapped to a genome

Mapped reads are counted per gene

  • Done with e.g. htseq
  • Coverage is counted -> counts table

A lot of this processing can be done in R!

(I didn't know this either!) http://biocluster.ucr.edu/~rkaundal/workshops/R_mar2016/RNAseq.html

Analysing and comparing expression levels

  • Various tools available
  • Well known, powerful, easy to use (and in R!): edgeR and DESeq
  • DESeq takes into account absolute expression level in variance calculations
  • Written by Michael Love, Simon Anders, Wolfgang Huber (Genome Biol, 2014)

DESeq2 input

  • Counts table
  • Study design

Prepare the analysis

counts <- read.table(
  "20180910_deseq2_counts.csv",
  header=T,
  sep=',',
  row.names=1)

design <- read.table(
  "20180910_deseq2_design.csv",
  header=T,
  sep=',',
  row.names=1)

Run DESeq to make a DESeq dataset

  • countData: the counts table
  • colData: your study design
  • design: a linear model (difference between treatment, controlling for sex)
# apply DESeq
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(
  countData=counts, 
  colData=design, 
  design=~sex+treatment)

dds <- DESeq(dds)

# filter low read counts
dds <- dds[ rowSums(counts(dds)) > 1, ]

Differential expression analysis

alpha <- 0.05
res <- results(dds, alpha = alpha)

Fold Change

  • log2 fold change: A vs B
  • if log2FoldChange > 0: A is higher
  • if log2FoldChange < 0: B is higher

# significant p values
res.sig <- res[res$padj<alpha & is.na(res$padj)==F,]

# DSX-RNAi expression increased (DSX downregulates)
res.sig.dsx <- res.sig[res.sig$log2FoldChange > 0,]

# CTRL-RNAi expression increased (DSX upregulates)
res.sig.ctrl <- res.sig[res.sig$log2FoldChange < 0,]

Add a 'group' variable

design$group <- paste0(design$sex,design$treatment)

New DESeq analysis with group variable

# Apply DESeq
dds.group <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(
  countData=counts, 
  colData=design, 
  design=~group)

dds.group <- DESeq(dds.group)
dds.group <- dds.group[ rowSums(counts(dds.group)) > 1, ]

# Extract results: for males and females
res.male <- results(dds.group, contrast=c("group","malectrl","maledsx"), alpha=alpha)
res.female <- results(dds.group, contrast=c("group","femalectrl","femaledsx"), alpha=alpha)

Males vs females

# extract significant results
res.male.sig <- res.male[res.male$padj<alpha & is.na(res.male$padj)==F,]
res.female.sig <- res.female[res.female$padj<alpha & is.na(res.female$padj)==F,]

Comparing samples

  • Counts tables are absolute values
  • Normalizing for sequencing depth is needed for comparisons
  • Gene length required “official” values (RPKM, FPKM, TPM…)
  • But, quick and dirty…
# normalize and transform
nt <- normTransform(dds)
assay(nt)
